<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="PSA" stage="Final" version="A">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2015-05-15 06:05:29Z" when="2015-05-15 06:05:29Z" stage="Final">Group 1 (1,19,23,24,100,121,150) Consultant checked with Catherine Rountree (by proxy) at UBB in Kupang 30 April 2015 with Chuck &amp; 3 UNSs selected by June; passed by email 15 May 2015</Message>
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2015-11-04 04:09:22Z" when="2015-11-04 04:09:22Z" stage="Draft">Gab has asked us to work on Ps. 103, 25, 95 and Nicean Creed (Constantinople) next.</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Lagu Puji dong</p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Lagu Puji dong<bt>Praise Songs</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(hist) Team checked and UNS checked"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">(hist) Team checked and UNS checked in 2009; BT by Chuck Dec 2014 to include in first batch.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(hist) Group 1 (1,19,23,24,100,121,150) Consultant checked"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">(hist) Group 1 (1,19,23,24,100,121,150) Consultant checked with Catherine Rountree (by proxy) at UBB in Kupang 30 April 2015 with Chuck &amp; 3 UNSs selected by June.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Orang yang idop babae deng Tuhan, nanti ontong<bt>People who live in right relationship with God2, will be fortunate/advantage/profit</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Orang yang ontong batúl, andia:<bt>Person/people who are truly fortunate/advantage/profit/blessed, are those: [EXEG: Heb. 'ashre ‘how blessed’ = ‘how fortunate (in God's eyes)’ see discussion in TH and LXX equiv. mapping to /Gk. makarios/ in beatitudes. ‘Happy’ is not part of the core meaning. TWOT “to be envied”. Posture of “walk” “stand” “sit” is for poetic parallelism, not in focus.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang sonde iko dengar orang jahat pung nasiat,<bt>who do not follow/participate listening/go along with the advice of evil people, [NOTE to daughter translations: not use /dong/ because generic/umum/general state of affairs, not specific groups of people. BUT your lg may mark generics with a plural, like English does.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang sonde iko bekin orang pakane'o pung jalan idop,<bt>who do not follow/participate doing twisted/immoral/evil3 people's way of life,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng sonde iko bagabung deng tukang olok-olok pung mau-mau.<bt>and don't follow/participate joining with scoffers/habitually or characteristically sarcastic (people's) desires/will/ways.  [EXEG: ‘seat’ also ‘assembly’ (NET note); TH ‘join or associate with’ TH ‘go along with’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`atsat: advice of, counsel of, plan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`atsat: advice of, counsel of, plan of, scheme of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`amad: he [does not] stand"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`amad: he [does not] stand</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'ashre (pl constr): fortunes, fortunate, blessed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'ashre (pl constr): fortunes, fortunate, blessed is; introduction to a word of blessing.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rəsha`iym: wicked ones, criminals. TWOT: used"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rəsha`iym: wicked ones, criminals. TWOT: used in parallel with almost every Hebrew word for sin, evil, and iniquity. The word functions also as an adjective to designate in concrete terms the actions and conduct of a type of person. Sometimes context points to the attitude and intention of people. Primarily, rasha` is an objective fact, rather than a subjective phenomenon. The measure of rasha` is its contrast with the character and attitude of God. The questions in Abraham's intercession imply that God is against rasha` (wicked) people. So does Ex 23:7; Job 9:22; Ps 37:28; Ezk 33:11; Mic 6:10. Wicked people were guilty of violation of the social rights of others, for they were violent, oppressive, greedy, engaged in plotting against and trapping poor people, and quite willing to murder to gain their ends. In a word, they threatened the community. They were dishonest in business and in the courtroom.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chaTTa'iym: professional sinners, habitual sinners"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">chaTTa'iym: professional sinners, habitual sinners</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="halakh ... `amad ... yashav progression."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">halakh ... `amad ... yashav progression. Implies a choice.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="derekh: here, the kind of life"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">derekh: here, the kind of life sinners live</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mowshav: seat, assembly. NET: Here the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mowshav: seat, assembly. NET: Here the Hebrew term moshav, although often translated "seat" (cf. NEB, NIV), appears to refer to the whole assembly of evildoers. The word also carries the semantic nuance "assembly" in Ps 107:32, where it is in synonymous parallelism with qahal, "assembly".</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yashav (yshb): sit; join in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yashav (yshb): sit; join in the discussion, participate in the deliberations</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="letsim: babbler, scoffer; worse than a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">letsim: babbler, scoffer; worse than a sinner (Proverbs high nose; ack jalike odda peopo, dey junk; ack stuck up, stuck up bugga). NET: The Hebrew word refers to arrogant individuals (Prov 21:24) who love conflict (Prov 22:10) and vociferously reject wisdom and correction (Prov 1:22; 9:7–8; 13:1; 15:12).</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Te orang hati lurus talalu suka balajar TUHAN pung Kata-kata dong.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) people with straight livers (=righteous/just/honest) really like to/enjoy learning/studying the LORD's Words/Sayings/Teachings (=God's Word). [EXEG: ‘learn’ suggested by TH and NET note, plus context of following clause. ‘Good person/people’ implied high level category of ‘righteous’ in constrast with ‘wicked’ as noted in TH from vs.5-6.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ais dong pikir dalam-dalam dia pung isi siang-malam.<bt>And then they think/ponder deeply its contents daytime-nighttime (=constantly).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pikir dalam-dalam = think deeply, meditate,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">pikir dalam-dalam = think deeply, meditate, renungkan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="towrah: teaching, content of teaching, law,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">towrah: teaching, content of teaching, law, rules</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cheftso: his joy, pleasure, delight. NET:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">cheftso: his joy, pleasure, delight. NET: In light of the following line, which focuses on studying the Lord’s law, one might translate, "he finds pleasure in studying the LORD’s commands." However, even if one translates the line this way, it is important to recognize that mere study and intellectual awareness are not ultimately what bring divine favor. Study of the law is metonymic here for the correct attitudes and behavior that should result from an awareness of and commitment to God’s moral will; thus "obeying" has been used in the translation rather than "studying."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yehgeh: mutter, read in an undertone,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yehgeh: mutter, read in an undertone, ponder by talking to oneself; meditate, devise, muse, imagine (in 2:1). JG: Silent reading is a much later invention: Augustine was surprised when Bishop Ambrose, who led him to Christ, read the Bible without mumbling to himself or moving his lips [Confessions].</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Orang macam bagitu sama ke pohon satu<bt>People of that sort are like a tree</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang tatanam di kali idop pung pinggir,<bt>which is planted along the side/bank of a living river, [NOTE to daughter translations: discuss difference between ‘dry stream bed’ (common in these parts) vs. ‘stream of running water’ supplying continuous fresh water (as per TH). Being a semi-arid region, in many local lgs the word for ‘river’ does not necessarily imply there is water in it.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kali idop ~ kali mati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">kali idop ~ kali mati</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang kasi kaluar bua pas dia pung musim,<bt>which gives out/puts forth fruit during its (normal/expected) season.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng dia pung daon sonde tau layu.<bt>and its leaves don't (ever) wither/shrivel. [Lit: don't know how to wither.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Samua yang dia bekin tu, jadi.<bt>Everything s/he does/makes, happens/succeeds/comes into being/fruition. [EXEG: subject of this sentence is contextually ‘the righteous’ moving away from the tree image (NET note).] [NOTE to daughter translations: careful to avoid the ambiguity of /samua jadi abis/ 1) everything has complete success, 2) everything comes to an end.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`aleho: its leaves, foliage"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`aleho: its leaves, foliage</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shatul (partcpl): planted, transplanted"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shatul (partcpl): planted, transplanted</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="peleg: artificial water-channel, canal. Most streams"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">peleg: artificial water-channel, canal. Most streams in Hawaii are intermittent, but the water ditches are kept full the year round because they are essential for agriculture.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yibol (nbl): wither and fall"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yibol (nbl): wither and fall</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yitsliach: be successful, succeed, bring to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yitsliach: be successful, succeed, bring to a successful conclusion, make someone prosper. Not just talking about money.</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeremia 17:8</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Ma orang jahat dong sonde bagitu.<bt>But evil people are not like that. [NOTE: Compare HCE which spells out reduced adverbial clause: “not like God's people” (the righteous)]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te dong sama ke uuk yang angin fuu buang.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) they are like chaff which the wind blows away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadiok: some say chaff, some say"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">kadiok: some say chaff, some say the small broken bits of rice, but this needs a stronger wind to blow away. So changed to uuk, which is the husks that blow away when winnowing. (cf. Matt. 3:12)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rəsha`iym: as in verse 1"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rəsha`iym: as in verse 1</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qamots: chaff from threshing wheat and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">qamots: chaff from threshing wheat and barley, economically useless and a nuisance. Not roots.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tidfennuw: [wind] drives [junks] away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tidfennuw: [wind] drives [junks] away</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Jadi, nanti kalo Tuhan putus samua orang dong pung parkara,<bt>So (consequently) later when God2 decides every person's case, [EXEG: Is this judgement 1) getting into heaven by passing through final judgement, or 2) enduring temporal punishment on this earth? NET note argues for #2, but context of next proposition and Heb article ‘the judgement’ (= definite, known) argues for #1.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">orang jahat dong sonde lolos.<bt>evil people will not pass through (successfully, safely).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te dong sonde ada pung hak maso,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) they don't have the right to enter</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko bagabung deng Tuhan pung orang hati lurus dong.<bt>to join with God2 people who are straight livered (=righteous/just).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`adat (cs): gathering of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`adat (cs): gathering of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaqmuw: BDB maintain oneself; be established,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yaqmuw: BDB maintain oneself; be established, be confirmed; stand, endure</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bammishpaT: in the judgment, pronouncement of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">bammishpaT: in the judgment, pronouncement of judgment</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsaddiyqiym: a person whose conduct is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsaddiyqiym: a person whose conduct is examined and found to be unobjectionable, innocent, morally in the right, just and righteous in character. BDB just, righteous (in conduct and character); righteous (as justified and vindicated by God)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Te TUHAN ada jaga deng piara<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the LORD is guarding/watching and nurturing/raising [EXEG: TH notes ‘guards’ also has sense of ‘care, guides, takes care of, cherishes’.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">orang hati lurus dong pung jalan idop.<bt>people with straight livers' life path,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ma orang jahat dong iko jalan<bt>But evil people follow a/the path/way</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang nanti bekin dong ancor sandiri.<bt>which will later/eventually make them destroy themselves/become destroyed of their own accord. [EXEG: want sense of ‘will lead to destruction’. NLT, CEV, TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yowdea` (partcpl): one who knows. TWOT:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yowdea` (partcpl): one who knows. TWOT: In certain contexts it means "to distinguish." "To know good and evil" (Gen 3:5, 22) is the result of disobeying God. To distinguish between these is necessary for the king (II Sam 19:36). A child cannot distinguish between the left and right hands (Jon 4:11) nor between good and evil (Deut 1:39; Isa 7:15).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="derekh: way, manner of living, life"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">derekh: way, manner of living, life style</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="to'ved: lost, astray, lose one's way"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">to'ved: lost, astray, lose one's way (derek Ps 2:12), near to ruin, perish, be ruined, be carried off, broken</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsaddiyqiym: righteous over sinners"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsaddiyqiym: righteous over sinners</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah kasi tunju diri di Dia pung cipta'an deng dalam Dia pung Kata-kata<bt>God reveals Himself in His creation and in His Words/Sayings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="19" />
      <v n="1" />
      <span class="Italic">Pasán kasi orang yang pimpin lagu dong: Lagu Puji ni, Daud yang karang.</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">Instructions to the person who leads the songs: this Praise Song (*Psalm), Daud is the one who composed it.</span> [NOTE on versification: The English versions all start vs.1 below at vs.2 and have 14 verses. The Hebrew and Indonesian versions start vs.1 here, and have 15 verses. We follow the Heb and Indonesian.]</bt>
      <Annotation class="General" selectedText="mnatstseaH (pi`el partcpl): the one leading;">
        <Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mnatstseaH (pi`el partcpl): the one leading; but could also mean "in an elevated tone" for manner rather than a designation of a participant.</Message>
      </Annotation>
      <Annotation class="General" selectedText="in titles, l- indicates either the">
        <Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">in titles, l- indicates either the author or the producer. By the choirmaster, in honor of David? By David, for the choirmaster to perform?</Message>
      </Annotation>
      <Annotation class="General" selectedText="mizmor: psalm. Book out in 2003">
        <Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mizmor: psalm. Book out in 2003 on Music in Ancient Palestine, covering instruments and styles.</Message>
      </Annotation>
      <Annotation class="General" selectedText="Major break at verse 8, and">
        <Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">Major break at verse 8, and also at 14, maybe 12 and a few others.</Message>
      </Annotation>
      <Annotation class="General" selectedText="Major break at verse 7. UBS">
        <Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">Major break at verse 7. UBS "two different compositions: one, a hymn celebrating God's glory as revealed by the sky and the sun (verses 1-6), and the other, a poem in praise of the Law, in which Yahweh's will is revealed (verses 7-14). The two differ in content, style, and poetic meter. Most scholars think that the first poem is considerably older, since it reflects themes similar to those of Near Eastern mythologies, while the second one reflects a time in which the written Law (the Torah) was already the basis of the faith of Israel."</Message>
      </Annotation>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Langit anteru<bt>The whole/entire sky/heavens [HCE everything you see... ??]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">kasi tunju Tuhan Allah pung hebat.<bt>shows/reveals God's amazingness/glory. [EXEG: ‘glory’ here]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Samua yang ada di sorga<bt>Everything that is in heaven2</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">kasi lia Dia pung hasil karjá.<bt>shows/demonstrates the results/success/fruit of His work.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mSaprim (pi`el partcpl): the ones recounting,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mSaprim (pi`el partcpl): the ones recounting, telling. Von Rad: "The world proclaims itself before God as a created thing." Romans 1 tells more about what this all means. Some oppose the idea of a natural theology, and by itself it is not enough to lead a person to salvation; it doesn't show incarnation or redemption. But it is something the Spirit uses to draw people to Christ, and it is part of a total theology.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Chiasm."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">Chiasm.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kəvod: (that which causes) honor, greatness."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">kəvod: (that which causes) honor, greatness. In this case it is not the glory of a theophany, but the enormous works of creation.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ma`əseh: deed, work"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ma`əseh: deed, work</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yadayw (dual): his hands"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yadayw (dual): his hands</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maggid (ngd hif partcpl): what announces"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">maggid (ngd hif partcpl): what announces</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raqia`: expanse"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">raqia`: expanse</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Kalo kotong taliti bae-bae, na,<bt>If/when we-inc examine [it] carefully, na,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dari hari ke hari kotong dapa tau hal baru.<bt>from day to day (=every day) we can know/understand new things.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dari hari ke hari ~ dari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">dari hari ke hari ~ dari malam pi malam (kotong mete)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dari malam pi malam kotong dapa katumu hal<bt>From night to night (=every night) we can encounter/discover things</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">yang kasi tunju Tuhan pung hebat.<bt>that show/reveal/display God's greatness/amazingness/glory. [EXEG: making higher level theme explicit. See discussion in TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yabbia` (nb` hif): cause to bubble"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yabbia` (nb` hif): cause to bubble up, like water coming out of a spring</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'omer: saying. The 'omer ... 'eyn-'omer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'omer: saying. The 'omer ... 'eyn-'omer pair with verse 3 is like an oxymoron; speaking but not speaking.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəHawweh (Hwh pi`el): gives information"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yəHawweh (Hwh pi`el): gives information</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Biar sonde ada yang ba'omong,<bt>Even though there is no-one who speaks,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sonde pake kata-kata,<bt>there are no words/sayings,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng sonde ada pung suara,<bt>and there is no voice/sound,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'omer: speaking"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'omer: speaking</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dvarim: words, matters"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">dvarim: words, matters</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bli: negation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">bli: negation</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nishma` (nif`al partcpl): is heard"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">nishma` (nif`al partcpl): is heard</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qolam: their voice"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">qolam: their voice</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />ma itu pasán tasiar pi anteru dunya,<bt>nevetheless that message spreads throughout the entire world,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sama ke ada yang kasi tau sang kotong,<bt>just as if there were [someone] who tells/explains [it] to us-inc,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng itu kata-kata tasiar sampe di dunya pung huk-huk.<bt>and those words/sayings spread to the point of reaching the corners of the earth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yatsa': go out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yatsa': go out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qawwam: their measuring line (variant is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">qawwam: their measuring line (variant is qowlam "their voice," but it is likely that qawwam alliterates with qowlam in verse 3). Most take it as a paraphrase of 'omer (Kraus). It may also point to the orderliness of the universe, or the most distant places in the world.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qtseh: end, border CHECK CHIASM (no"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">qtseh: end, border CHECK CHIASM (no block to understanding, but no recognition of pattern)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tevel: earth, continent"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tevel: earth, continent</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="millehem (milah): their words"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">millehem (milah): their words</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shemesh: sun, the most impressive part"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shemesh: sun, the most impressive part of hasshamayim.</Message></Annotation><note reference="19:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Roma 10:18</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Tuhan su ator tampa tenga di sorga kasi matahari.<bt>God2 has already arranged for a place to stay in heaven2/sky for the sun.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lashemesh: for the sun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">lashemesh: for the sun</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sam (sim perf): put"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">sam (sim perf): put</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'ohel: tent; house, habitation of any"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'ohel: tent; house, habitation of any kind (not like Haleakala "the house acquired by the sun" in the Hawaiian Maui story, where a mountain peak becomes the sun's home after Maui lassos him and insists that he slow down so Maui's mother can get her clothes dry. SS grew up on the slopes of Haleakal)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Ais matahari nae papagi,<bt>So/then the sun rises in the early morning,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sama ke satu baroit laki-laki<bt>like a bridegroom</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">yang kaluar dari tenda kawin.<bt>who comes out from the wedding tent.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ju dia lari ukur kuat,<bt>And/then he runs with all his strength,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sama ke satu jago lari<bt>like a (running) champion</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">yang talalu samangat.<bt>who is inspired/enthusiastic/vigorous/joyfully determined.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chatan: bridegroom"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">chatan: bridegroom</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yotse' (partcpl): coming out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yotse' (partcpl): coming out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chuppato: canopy set up for the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">chuppato: canopy set up for the bride and bridegroom at a wedding. In modern Judaism the chupa is the canopy set up on four posts, and also the wedding ceremony (Glinert, The Joys of Hebrew); UBS takes it as "a temporary pavilion, or canopy, provided for newlyweds and set up in the groom's home" where presumably they spend their wedding night; bridal chamber (Holladay).</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yasis (sws): he rejoices"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yasis (sws): he rejoices</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gibor: strong, mighty, hero; in this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">gibor: strong, mighty, hero; in this case like an athlete</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'orach: path, course; race"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'orach: path, course; race</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Itu matahari nae dari langit pung ujung.<bt>That sun rises from one end/tip of the sky/heavens.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ais dia iko tarús dia pung jalan<bt>Then2 he/it continues going on its journey [NOTE: personified.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sampe di ujung sablá.<bt>until reaching the other end/tip.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sonde ada yang bisa sambunyi<bt>There is nobody/nothing that can hide</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dari dia pung panas.<bt>from his/its heat.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qtseh: end, boundary"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">qtseh: end, boundary</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="motsa'o: his exit, his exiting; the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">motsa'o: his exit, his exiting; the place the sun comes out of = the east</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tqufato: his solstitial point (farthest north"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tqufato: his solstitial point (farthest north and farthest south); its turning (Holladay, turn of the year at autumnal equinox, Exodus 34:22</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niStar (nif partcpl): is hidden; the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">niStar (nif partcpl): is hidden; the participles may indicate things that are continually going on.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chammato: its glow, its heat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">chammato: its glow, its heat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="There is a break in style"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">There is a break in style and diction here. Some have assumed two poems were put together, in good 19th century critical fashion. But the word choice may as well reflect a shift in thinking; nature teaches us some things we need to know; revelation teaches us what 'El is really like. The heavens declare 'El, almighty but unknowable; the Law declares Yahweh, the one who has a name and communicates with people. Both are part of the groundwork for Romans 1. Some rabbis felt that Torah is an act of God's mercy -- what it we didn't have it? We need it to survive here and hereafter.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />TUHAN pung atoran dong, sampurna,<bt>The LORD's regulations/laws, are complete/well-rounded, [NOTE: There is a break in style and diction here. Some have assumed two poems were put together, in good 19th century critical fashion. But the word choice may as well reflect a shift in thinking; nature teaches us some things we need to know; revelation teaches us what 'El is really like. The heavens declare 'El, almighty but unknowable; the Law declares Yahweh, the one who has a name and communicates with people. Both are part of the groundwork for Romans 1. Some rabbis felt that Torah is an act of God's mercy -- what if we didn't have it? We need it to survive here and hereafter.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te dong bekin sagár orang pung hati.<bt>cuz (elaboration) they refresh a person's liver (=seat of emotions and character).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">TUHAN pung parenta dong, kotong bisa parcaya,<bt>The LORD's commands, we-inc can believe/trust them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te dong bekin orang biasa-biasa dong jadi pintar.<bt>cuz (elaboration) they make normal/simple (=not educated or elíte) become clever/wise/capable.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`edot: witness, testimony, command"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`edot: witness, testimony, command</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="orang biasa-biasa - normal, simple, sederhana,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">orang biasa-biasa - normal, simple, sederhana, not sought out by the elíte or educated</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="torat: instruction, law; all roughly synonymous"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">torat: instruction, law; all roughly synonymous with all the other subjects</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tmimah: complete, blameless; the adjectives are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tmimah: complete, blameless; the adjectives are the key</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mshivat (shwb hif partcpl): bringing back,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mshivat (shwb hif partcpl): bringing back, renewing; refreshing, or resituating? Even more spectacular than the natural revelation. Deut 30:11-20.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ne'əmanah ('mn nif partcpl): being loyal,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ne'əmanah ('mn nif partcpl): being loyal, steadfast, reliable, trustworthy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maHkimat (Hkh hif partcpl): making wise"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">maHkimat (Hkh hif partcpl): making wise</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="peti: the clueless (in Proverbs, naive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">peti: the clueless (in Proverbs, naive but maybe instructable); parallel in form, quite divergent from the the first part. Is it only that peti that can profit? Or is peti the extreme case.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />TUHAN pung ajaran dong, batúl,<bt>The LORD's teachings are true,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te dong bekin sanáng orang pung hati.<bt>cuz (elaboration) they make glad/happy a person's liver.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">TUHAN pung parenta dong, jalás,<bt>The LORD's commands are clear,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te dong kasi taráng orang pung jalan idop.<bt>cuz (elaboration) they make clear/illuminate a person's life way/path. [EXEG: ‘enlightening the eyes’ = bringing understanding, TH, insight for life, NLT, NET.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`enayim: both eyes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`enayim: both eyes</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Or reverse: jalás - taráng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">Or reverse: jalás - taráng</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="piqqude: orders"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">piqqude: orders</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ysharim: right"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ysharim: right</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="msamməHe (smH pi`el partcpl): causing to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">msamməHe (smH pi`el partcpl): causing to rejoice, in line with hifils in passages</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mitswat: the command, precept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mitswat: the command, precept</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="barah: bright, pure, flawless; UBS right,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">barah: bright, pure, flawless; UBS right, clear, just; more to do with light than cleanness</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="m'irat ('wr hif partcpl): illuminating, giving"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">m'irat ('wr hif partcpl): illuminating, giving light; understanding? restoring strength?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="10" />Kalo kotong taku sang TUHAN,<bt>If/when we-inc fear the LORD,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">itu bekin barisi kotong pung hati,<bt>that cleanses/purifies our liver, [EXEG: ‘good’ from NCV, but ‘clean, pure’ is better match of Heb.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">deng dia pung guna maen jalan tarús-tarús.<bt>and his/its usefulness/benefits keep going on continually. [CHECK again if this makes sense]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">TUHAN pung putusan dong, lurus,<bt>The LORD's decisions are straight/honest/just (lurus: moral),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te samua putusan tu, adil.<bt>cuz (elaboration) all of those decisions are fair/just (adil: legal).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`omedet (fem partcpl): stand; stand (before),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`omedet (fem partcpl): stand; stand (before), i.e. serve, minister to; to be set over; to confide in; to stand by, defend; to stand firm, remain, endure; to resist; to persist, persevere; to stand still, stop; to stand up, arise; to be constituted, set, appointed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yir'at: fear, awe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yir'at: fear, awe</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Təhorah: clean; of precious metals: without"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">Təhorah: clean; of precious metals: without alloy of less precious substances: pure</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="la`ad: till forever"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">la`ad: till forever</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mishpate: decisions handed down by a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mishpate: decisions handed down by a judge</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'emet: firmness, faithfulness, truth"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'emet: firmness, faithfulness, truth</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsadqu: they are just, in the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsadqu: they are just, in the right</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yaHdaw: together, altogether"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yaHdaw: together, altogether</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Tuhan pung Kata-kata dong pung harga, lebe mahal dari mas.<bt>God2's Words'/Sayings have value/worth/price more expensive than gold.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dong pung nilei, lebe tinggi dari mas tulen.<bt>Their value2/assessment is higher than pure gold. [NOTE to daughter translations: each language has different words that collocate with ‘gold’, so don't let your team be sloppy and just blindly translate the words. Check the collocations.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dong pung rasa, lebe manis dari madu.<bt>Their taste/flavour/sensation is sweeter than honey.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dong pung manis, lebe dari madu utan yang malele dari dia pung sarang.<bt>Their sweetness is more/greater/better than wild honey that seeps/leaks from its nest/honeycomb.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neHəmadim (Hmd nif partcpl pl): to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">neHəmadim (Hmd nif partcpl pl): to be desired</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mizahav: gold, like 14 carat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mizahav: gold, like 14 carat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paz: pure gold, 24 carat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">paz: pure gold, 24 carat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rav: much, many"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rav: much, many</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mətuqim: sweet, sweeter than"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mətuqim: sweet, sweeter than</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dvash: honey, fruit syrup, dates, grapes,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">dvash: honey, fruit syrup, dates, grapes, figs</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nofet: honey straight from the comb"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">nofet: honey straight from the comb</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsufim: honeycomb"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsufim: honeycomb</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Beta ni, Tuhan Allah pung orang karjá.<bt>I here am a servant/worker of the Lord God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deng Tuhan pung Kata-kata dong kasi inga beta,<bt>And God2's Words/Sayings remind/warn me, [EXEG: ‘warned’ in Heb maps to be ‘reminded’ in Kupang and other lgs, which is polysemous 1) reminded, 2) warned; to lean it toward warned, we add the next clause.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko jang langgar Tuhan pung atoran.<bt>to not violate/transgress/step over the line of God2's regulations/laws.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dong ju kasi inga sang beta,<bt>They also remind/warn me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko beta bekin iko tarús Tuhan pung ajaran.<bt>so that I keep following/obeying God2's teachings.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te nanti Tuhan mau balas kasi berkat bam-banya,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later God2 will reciprocate/reward giving a great many *blessings,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sang orang yang dengar-dengar sang Dia.<bt>to people who listen to/obey Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`avdəkha: your servant, in the group"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`avdəkha: your servant, in the group of people faithful to Yahweh.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gam: moreover, what's more"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">gam: moreover, what's more</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nizhar (zhr nif partcpl): be warned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">nizhar (zhr nif partcpl): be warned</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bshamram (inf cs): in keeping them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">bshamram (inf cs): in keeping them</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'eqev: recompense"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'eqev: recompense</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rav: many, much"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rav: many, much</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />Sapa bisa tau dia pung sala dong samua?<bt>Who can know all of his *offences/wrongs/faults/sins? [CHECK: His own? NOISE: 3s pronoun in previous clause refers to God, so potential ambiguity here.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Beta sandiri sonde bisa tau.<bt>I myself cannot know [them (all)]. [EXEG: answering RQ]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Andia ko beta minta ko<bt>That is why I ask/request that</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tuhan hapus buang beta pung sala,<bt>God2 wipe away my *wrongs, [EXEG: TH, NCV, CEV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">yang beta bekin deng sonde sadar.<bt>that I do without being aware [of them].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shgi'ot: sins of ignorance"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shgi'ot: sins of ignorance</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yavin: to perceive, to notice, to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yavin: to perceive, to notice, to consider, to understand</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niStarot (Str nif partcpl): hidden things"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">niStarot (Str nif partcpl): hidden things</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="naqqeni (qnh pi`el imperv): to pronounce"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">naqqeni (qnh pi`el imperv): to pronounce innocent; to let go unpunished. Also 13</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />Deng beta ju minta ko<bt>And I also ask/request that [NOTE: to make structure parallel to 12]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tuhan jaga sang beta,<bt>God2 guards/watches over me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko biar beta jang bekin sala<bt>so that I do not [+EMPH] do *wrong/s</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">yang beta ada kapingin mau bekin.<bt>that I am desiring to do.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Jaga ko biar itu sala dong<bt>Guard so that those wrongs</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">jang ator bale sang beta.<bt>do not control me in return/come back and control/manage me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ko biar beta sonde ada pung sala,<bt>So that I have no *wrong/sin,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng beta barisi dari dosa.<bt>and I am clean/pure from *sin (loan: for paralellism).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shəgiy'owt: errors"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shəgiy'owt: errors</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="zedim: insolent people, acts; presumptuous sins"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">zedim: insolent people, acts; presumptuous sins committed with full knowledge</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Həsk (imperv): to keep something or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">Həsk (imperv): to keep something or someone under control: to restrain, hold back, keep from, prevent, withhold, spare</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yimshlu (mshl): may they not rule"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yimshlu (mshl): may they not rule over me</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'az: then"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'az: then</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'eytam (tmm imperf): I will be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'eytam (tmm imperf): I will be complete, consumed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="niqqeti (nqh nif): I will be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">niqqeti (nqh nif): I will be free from punishment, blameless</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pesha`: rebellion, revolt; contesting, impeachment of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">pesha`: rebellion, revolt; contesting, impeachment of property</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rav: much, many"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rav: much, many</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />Biar ko kata-kata yang kaluar dari beta pung mulu,<bt>May the words/sayings which come out from my mouth,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng hal-hal yang beta pikir dalam beta pung hati,<bt>and the things that I think in my liver,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">samua bekin sanáng Tuhan pung hati.<bt>all make God2's liver happy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te TUHAN tu, sama ke satu batu bésar,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the LORD, is like a great rock,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang sonde tagoyang.<bt>which does not move/wobble/be unstable.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng Tuhan tu, yang kasi salamat sang beta,<bt>And God2/the Lord, is the one who *saves/rescues me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng tabús ame sang beta,<bt>and (completely/successfully) *redeems me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">waktu beta sandiri sonde mampu.<bt>when I myself am not able/capable. [EXEG: explication of Heb ‘kinsmen-redeemer’, BDB, TWOT.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yihyu: may they be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yihyu: may they be</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ratson: delight, satisfaction; will, pleasure; goodwill,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ratson: delight, satisfaction; will, pleasure; goodwill, favour</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'imre-fi: the things my mouth utters"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'imre-fi: the things my mouth utters</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hegyon: muttering, resounding"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">hegyon: muttering, resounding</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsuri: my rock"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsuri: my rock</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="go'əli: my redeemer (like Boaz in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">go'əli: my redeemer (like Boaz in Ruth); the one who can make a claim for me, had the duty of providing for a relative who needed help, deliverer</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan tu, sama ke gambala yang bae<bt>God2  is like a good shepherd</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="23" />
      <span class="Italic">Lagu Puji ni, Daud yang karang.</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">This Praise Song (=Psalm), Daud is the one who composed it.</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="1" />TUHAN tu, beta pung gambala yang piara ame sang beta.<bt>The LORD is my shepherd who takes (good) care of me. [See alt HCE simile structure. Clearer?]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Andia ko beta sonde kurang satu apa ju.<bt>That is why I am not lacking in anything (at all).</bt></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\BK00004c.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Gambala yang bae<bt>A good shepherd</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mizmor: a psalm"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mizmor: a psalm</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ro`iy (partcpl): innovative; don't usually use"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ro`iy (partcpl): innovative; don't usually use 1st person. Kings were thought of as the shepherds of their people; but David puts a twist on it.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'echsar: diminish, lack, be empty, do"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'echsar: diminish, lack, be empty, do without</Message></Annotation></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Dia foo bawa sang beta pi padang rumput,<bt>He herds me going to grassy fields, [EXEG: sense of lush fields to graze in lazily]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ko biar beta bisa barenti cape di situ.<bt>so that I can rest there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dia antar bawa sang beta,<bt>He leads/escorts me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pi minum di mata aer yang tanáng.<bt>to drink at a calm/still/quiet (untroubled/undisturbed) spring. [EXEG: check imagery; check collocations. Not a stagnant pool; not a raging torrent; fresh water is replenished gently; easy to drink; free from threats. TH]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="n'ot deshe': in lovely places of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">n'ot deshe': in lovely places of new green grass; characteristic places of the green stuff, place where you expect it, where something hangs out. A shepherd knows all these places. (The job also attracted a pretty motley crew of day laborers.)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Make shure it's clear that he's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">Make shure it's clear that he's following the shepherd metaphor.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yarbiytseniy (rbts hif): he makes me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yarbiytseniy (rbts hif): he makes me lie down, he lets me lie down, he makes it possible</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'al-mey mnuchowt (pl): to the bank"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'al-mey mnuchowt (pl): to the bank of waters of rest, restful waters, water where I can rest</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yənahəleni he leads me, *guides me,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yənahəleni he leads me, *guides me, helps me along (especially the handicapped). BDB lead to a watering-place or station and cause to rest there</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Dunya Model Baru 7:17</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Dia kasi kuat sang beta,<bt>He strengthens me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng kasi beta idop baru.<bt>and gives me new life. [EXEG: see TH, NRSV note, CEV, nthb: Heb. əshowvev: he causes my life to return, gives me new vitality, restores my power to live; my spirits are revived, refreshes me; invigorates.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dia kasi tunju sang beta jalan idop yang batúl,<bt>He shows/reveals to me the true path of life/the right way to live,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal Dia tu gambala yang mau jaga Dia pung nama bae.<bt>because He is a shepherd who wants to guard His good name/reputation. [EXEG: TH, NLT, NET, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yəshowvev: he causes my life to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yəshowvev: he causes my life to return, gives me new vitality, restores my power to live; my spirits are revived, refreshes me; invigorates</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yancheni (nchh hif): lead"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yancheni (nchh hif): lead</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ma`əgəley-tsedeq: in tracks, ruts that are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ma`əgəley-tsedeq: in tracks, ruts that are right, normal, well-worn path, suitable, trustworthy. Not "ways that lead me to do the right thing," but "ways that are suitable for me"; `egel cart.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsedeq: right. UBS: Tsedeq is not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsedeq: right. UBS: Tsedeq is not normally part of the image of being shown a particular path, but adds another level of meaning at that point. Possibly "the best path," not chaotic, but obvious. Also, he's the king leading Israel, though he downplays this.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lma`an shmo: for the sake of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">lma`an shmo: for the sake of his name, for the sake of his reputation; God has the reputation of doing what he promises</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Biar lai beta ada jalan<bt>Even though I am walking/going</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">di jurang yang paling galáp,<bt>in the darkest ravine, [EXEG: “the shadow of death” = Heb. idiom: darkness; TH, NRSV, NLT, NCV, NET; BDB ‘narrow gorge’ (but TWOT says elongated flat-bottom); context seems to imply a fearful/terrifying place; a dangerous place to take sheep. Kupang has a word for &lt;(dangerous) ravine&gt;, but not for &lt;broad valley&gt;.]</bt><note reference="23:4a" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Bahasa Ibrani di sini tulis bilang, &lt;&lt;jurang yang galáp gulita&gt;&gt;, yang maksud &lt;&lt;tampa yang bawa rasa talalu taku&gt;&gt;. Septuaginta (LXX) terjemahkan pake ungkapan &lt;&lt;lémba yang bawa mati pung bayangan&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Hebrew language here writes saying, &lt;&lt;pitch dark ravine&gt;&gt;, which implies &lt;&lt;a place that evokes a feeling of great fear&gt;&gt;. The Septuagint (LXX) translated that using the phrase &lt;&lt;valley (loan) which brings the shadow of death&gt;&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">ma beta sonde taku ame deng jahat apa-apa,<bt>but I am not (successfully/truly) afraid of any evil.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal Tuhan, Lu ada jalan sama-sama deng beta.<bt>because God2, You are going/walking/journeying together with me. [DISCOURSE: Heb shifts from 3rd person ‘Lord’ to 2nd person ‘you’ at this point, shifting it into direct prayer/praise. In some lgs of eastern Indonesia it could be rude to do so. Also 3rd person is the polite/respectful form of direct address in all these lgs, not 2s pron.] [STYLE: this approach seen as the best compromise. UNSs otherwise did not know that this was addressing God directly.]</bt><note reference="23:4b" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Di ayat 4-6 bahasa Ibrani pake orang kedua tunggal “Lu”, ko sambayang langsung pi Tuhan. Botong pake “Tuhan, Lu...” di sini, ko biar pambaca dong tau Daud ada sambayang di sini. Kalo sonde, orang pikir Daud cuma omong <span class="Italic">so'al</span> Tuhan sa.<bt>In verses 4-6 the Ibrani language uses the second person singular “You”, to pray directly to God2. We-exc use “God2, You...” here, so that readers know Daud is praying here. If not, people think that Daud is just talking <span class="Italic">about</span> God2.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Beta rasa aman,<bt>I feel safe/secure (from external threats),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal Tuhan ada pegang tongkat deng kayu kudung.<bt>because God2 is holding the walking staff (also used for defensive fighting)/sceptor and the short stick (lexicalised = club). [EXEG: ‘rod and staff’ TH, CEV note; order changed for RL naturalness and focus; ‘comfort’ TH, NET note.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bəgey' tsalmawet: through a valley of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">bəgey' tsalmawet: through a valley of darkness (Amos 5:8) from tselem 'shadow, something shadowy, form without substance': total darkness, possibly 'dark as death' since mwt is part of the compound, though that doesn't mean it has the sense 'death' in that context. Gey' is often in the construct with the name of valleys: of Travelers, of Murder, of Vision. This one is still part of the sheep imagery: dangerous places to take livestock, large carnivores like lions or wolves hang around water holes.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'atah: you, shift from &quot;him&quot; in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'atah: you, shift from "him" in the first part</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shivtkha (shevet): the stick, staff, rod"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shivtkha (shevet): the stick, staff, rod of a shepherd, teacher, scepter, weapon, tool; club to drive off wild animals. Short cudgel, heavy end sheathed in metal, possibly suspended over shoulder. TWOT: used for beating cumin (Isa 28:27), as a weapon (II Sam 23:21), and as a shepherd's implement either to muster or count sheep (Lev 27:32; Ezk 20:37), or to protect them (Ps 23:4; Mic 7:14). In Ps 23:4 it is used metaphorically of the Lord's protection of his servant as he walks in paths of righteousness.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mish`enet: support, staff, stick used for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mish`enet: support, staff, stick used for the sick, the elderly, a ruler, an angel; walking stick. Single piece, two different functions: defend, guide? TWOT: Staff. Elijah had one (II Kgs 4:29-31), as did the Angel of the Lord in Jud 6:21 and the nobles depicted in Num 21:18. In Ps 23:4, the Shepherd's staff is a comfort to His sheep.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yinachmuni (nchm pi`el): comfort in case"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yinachmuni (nchm pi`el): comfort in case of death, reassure; mother to child; feel protected, safe</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Tuhan bekin pesta kasi sang beta,<bt>God2 is making a feast/party for me, [DISCOURSE: shifts away from shepherd imagery to victory feast or a royal banquet, or (Anderson) a fellowship dinner. The mention of ‘enemies’ suggests the former. Either way God shows his special favour. Because the context is disputed, we try and leave open all these options, and focus on the favour God is showing, regardless of the context.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">di beta pung musu dong pung muka,<bt>in front of my enemies,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko biar dong dapa lia bilang,<bt>so that they can see that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Tuhan mau kasi tunju Dia pung hati bae sang beta.<bt>God2 wants to show/demonstrate His good liver (goodness/kindness/generosity/grace) to me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tagal Tuhan mau kasi tunju Dia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">Tagal Tuhan mau kasi tunju Dia pung hati bae sang beta,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="andia ko Dia bekin pesta kasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">andia ko Dia bekin pesta kasi sang beta,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="di beta pung musu dong pung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">di beta pung musu dong pung muka/ko biar beta pung musu dong dapa lia.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Tuhan ju taro minya di beta pung kapala,<bt>God2 also puts oil on my head,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal Dia mau kasi tunju hormat sang beta<bt>because He wants to show honour/respect to me, [EXEG: see discussion in TH and NET note.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sama ke tuan ruma yang bae tarima tamu deng hormat.<bt>like a good master of the house receives guests with respect. [CULTURE: elaborating unknown concept.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Tuhan isi beta pung galás sampe ponu rata,<bt>God2 fills my glass to the brim,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal Dia mau po'a berkat bam-banya kasi sang beta.<bt>because He wants to pour out many *blessings on/to me. [EXEG: meaning disputed, ‘overflows’, ‘to the brim’, or ‘satisfied, give me all I can drink’. 2nd is most strongly supported, BART exeg. note. CULTURE: problem, filling full doesn't really convey the intended imagery of ‘generosity, heaping blessing’ Discuss with team.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta`rokh (`rk): lay things out in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ta`rokh (`rk): lay things out in rows, put in order, prepare</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shulchan: table, like a banquet, to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shulchan: table, like a banquet, to show appreciation and respect; the bad guys see that God is taking good care of him and they can't do anything about it. Could reflect the Abigail story; she fed David in a dangerous place. Could also be a sacrificial table for a thanksgiving offering to celebrate his release from opposition by his enemies, set up in the Temple, ready to enjoy a feast. The enemies are there too, but he has been exonerated, possibly by a court, and they can't do anything about the result of a fair verdict.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsorəray: my enemies"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsorəray: my enemies</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="disshanta (pi`el): you have anointed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">disshanta (pi`el): you have anointed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shemesh: olive oil. The good host"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shemesh: olive oil. The good host would greet an honored guest by putting oil on his head (Luke 7:46). Same spirit as in welcoming someone with a lei, but honoring someone by putting oil on his head is culturally incomprehensible and would be misunderstood as a weird, unthinkable action. JG: Oil would not be used here, but a lei would convey the same feeling of welcome and respect.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kowSiy: my cup"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">kowSiy: my cup</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rəwayah: saturation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rəwayah: saturation</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Beta parcaya bilang, Tuhan ada mau kasi tunju Dia pung hati bae sang beta,<bt>I believe that God2 is desiring to show His good liver (goodness/kindness/generosity/grace) to me, [DISCOURSE: Heb still in 2s. KM combination mirrors range of Heb combination, even though the two pieces individually are slightly different.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng mau kasi tunju Dia pung rasa kasian sang beta,<bt>and wants to show His pity/mercy to me, [EXEG: Note on /hesed/ from Gen 24:12: from TH &amp; CEV/TEV; TWOT Heb. /hesed/ is "loyalty...fidelity to covenantal obligations real or implied...freely given...kindness...on the basis of a relationship...lovingkindness"; Speiser "true loyalty"; referring to Abraham's promise that God would look after the servant in vs.7 here. (/hesed/ in v12, 27, (42 success), 49, (56 success)].</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sapanjang beta idop di ini dunya.<bt>as long as I live in this world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="salama = KM? sapanjang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">salama = KM? sapanjang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng beta ju parcaya bilang, beta dapa tampa<bt>And I also believe that I (will) get/obtain a place</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dalam Tuhan pung ruma sandiri.<bt>in God2's own house. [EXEG: ‘house of the Lord’ = 1) I'm part of God's family/household or royal household (consistent with imagery in vs.5), 2) I will spend a significant part of my time in earthly tabernacle and later God's temple (in Jerusalem). Context favours first, but conventionalised phrasing favours second.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Deng bagitu, beta mau tenga di situ tarús-tarús.<bt>In that way, I want to stay/live there continually/forever. [EXEG: ‘length of days’ Heb idiom TH, NET + note, NRSV.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'akh: indeed, surely (emphatic)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'akh: indeed, surely (emphatic)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tov vachesed: goodness and covenant solidarity/love"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tov vachesed: goodness and covenant solidarity/love</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yirdəfuwniy: will pursue me. UBS: means"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yirdəfuwniy: will pursue me. UBS: means "to accompany," "to go with"; it should not be given the meaning of "to pursue, to run after."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="vashavti: I will continue to return,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">vashavti: I will continue to return, hang out; come back. NET: The verb form (veshavtiy) is a Qal perfect (with vav [w] consecutive), first common singular, from (shuv, “return”) and should be translated, “and I will return.” But this makes no sense when construed with the following phrase, “in the house of the LORD.” The term (shuv) appears only here with the following phrase (bevet). The form should be emended to (veshivtiy; an infinitive construct from yashav, “live”) with pronominal suffix) or to (veyashavtiy; a Qal perfect with vav [w] consecutive, first common singular, from yshb [see BHS, note c]). In either case one could then translate, “and I will live [in the house of the LORD].” The phrase “in the house” frequently follows the verb yshb in the OT.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beyt-y': the Temple or Tent (not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">beyt-y': the Temple or Tent (not used of Heaven in the Old Testament)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lə'orekh yamim: length of days, long"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">lə'orekh yamim: length of days, long life; the rest of my life</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sapa yang bole maso pi dalam Tuhan pung Ruma Sambayang?<bt>Who may enter into God2's House of Prayer/Worship?</bt><note reference="24" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lagu Puji ni, satu liturgi yang dong pake waktu mau nae pi atas gunung ko maso pi dalam Tuhan pung Tenda Sambayang. Jama'at dong babalas deng kapala agama dong. Huruf miring dalam kurung sonde ada dalam tulisan bahasa Ibrani asli. Ma orang yang pintar dong bilang ini Lagu Puji babalas bagini.<bt>This Praise Song is a liturgy which they used when they were about to go up the hill/mountain to enter into God's Tent of Prayer. The congregation responded back and forth with/to the *priests. The slanted letters in brackets are not written in the original Ibrani language writings. But experts/knowledgable people say this Praise song responds back-and-forth in this way. [EXEG: TH, HCE, JEG, Israeli rabbi.]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="24" />
      <span class="Italic">Lagu Puji ni, Daud yang karang.</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">This Praise Song (=Psalm), Daud is the one who composed it.</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="1" />Bumi deng dia pung isi samua,<bt>The earth and all that it contains,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">andia TUHAN pung milik.<bt>belongs to the LORD.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dunya anteru deng dia pung orang samua,<bt>The entire world and all of its people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">musti dengar ame sang Dia.<bt>must listen/obey Him. [EXEG: Q: Everybody else says “belong to him” vs Kupang “must obey Him.” Is that an idiomatic way to say they belong to Him? A: The Heb simply uses a possessive form, with [belong] marked as implied in BART. NRSV uses possessive /'s/; NLT &amp; CEV use “belongs to Him”. This is further complicated by being in a poetic parallelism structure, but only using one vb/possessive for both in Heb. In Timor region RLs, we have to structure this with two verbs for the parallelism. For people (as the possessed), saying they “obey/listen to” a king or leader is a common way of saying “they are his”, or “they belong to him”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mlo'ah: its fulness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mlo'ah: its fulness</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tevel: continents, land mass"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tevel: continents, land mass</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 10:26</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Te Dia yang taro ame darat di atas laut,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who placed the land upon the sea, [NOTE: The Hebrew view was that the deep ocean was under everything, except where the bases of the mountains reached down through it to the underworld.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dia yang bekin ame karíng di atas aer.<bt>He is the one who made the dry (land) on the water. [EXEG: Typical of parallelisms, seas and rivers here are simply a poetic reflection of two complementary parts of a Hebrew cosmological whole. TH, TWOT, BDB]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`al-: higher than, standing in front"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`al-: higher than, standing in front of a sitting person, in preference to, facing, against</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ysadah (pi`el): found, fix solid --"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ysadah (pi`el): found, fix solid -- dominating? based on?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nharot: not just rivers, but ocean"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">nharot: not just rivers, but ocean currents. The Hebrew view was that the deep ocean was under everything, except where the bases of the mountains reached down through it to the underworld.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ykhonneh (kwn pi`el): establish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">ykhonneh (kwn pi`el): establish</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Orang Ibrani dong pikir bilang, darat tu ta'apung di atas aer laut. Lia ju <span class="Italic">Carita Mula-mula</span> 1:6,9-10; 7:11; <span class="Italic">Kaluar dari Masir</span> 20:4; <span class="Italic">Lagu Puji dong</span> 136:6.<bt>The Ibrani people thought that, the land floated on top of the ocean water. See also <span class="Italic">Genesis</span> 1:6,9-10; 7:11; <span class="Italic">Exodus</span> 20:4; <span class="Italic">Psalms</span> 136:6. [EXEG: TH, NET note.]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />
      <span class="Italic">[Jama'at dong tanya bilang,]</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">[The congregation/people ask saying,]</span> [STYLE: back and forth between the priests and the people suggested to JEG by an Israeli rabbi.]</bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Kalo Dia yang bekin ame itu samua-samua, na, sapa yang ada pung hak<bt>&lt;&lt;If He is the one who made/did (accomplishment) all that, na, who is it that has the right [See HCE vs.3 the people ask; vs.4 the priests respond, TH also.] [EXEG: JEG Heb. mi-ya`leh: who will go up? Picture of pilgrims from all over coming together for a holy day, walking up the hill into Jerusalem and going on to where the Temple stood.] [OV had “If that's the case...”, but UNSs could not get the reference as vs.1-2.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nae pi atas TUHAN pung gunung,<bt>to ascend up the LORD's hill/mountain,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko angka puji sang Dia si situ?<bt>to lift praise to Him there? [EXEG: purpose suggested by TH. JEG note above.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng sapa yang ada pung hak<bt>And who is it that has the right</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">badiri di Dia pung Ruma Barisi,<bt>to stand in His Clean/Holy/Pure House, [EXEG: CEV, NCV, NET]</bt><note reference="24:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Iko orang yang pintar so'al Alkitab, &lt;Tuhan pung gunung&gt; tu, andia Sion, itu bukit di Yerusalem yang jadi Tuhan Allah pung Ruma Sambayang Pusat pung tampa. Alkitab bahasa Ibrani ju tulis bilang, &lt;tampa barisi&gt;, andia Ruma Sambayang Pusat ju.<bt>According to people knowledgable about the Bible (=experts) &lt;the Lord's mountain&gt;, is Sion, the hill in Yerusalem which is the place/location of God's *Temple (Main House of Worship). The Ibrani language Bible also writes saying, &lt;clean/holy place&gt;, that is, the *Temple. [EXEG: TH, CEV, NCV,]</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko sambayang sang Dia di situ?&gt;&gt;<bt>to *pray/worship Him there?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mi-ya`leh: who will go up? Picture"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mi-ya`leh: who will go up? Picture of pilgrims from all over coming together for a holy day, walking up the hill into Jerusalem and going on to where the Temple stood.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bahar-yhwh: another way of talking about"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">bahar-yhwh: another way of talking about the mountain with the Temple on top, also called Zion</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\LB00186c.tif" rtfFormat="width:3.5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Kapala agama pange orang ko datang sambayang<bt>A priest calls/summons people to come worship</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />
      <span class="Italic">[Kapala agama dong manyao bilang,]</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">The *priests (heads of religion) answer/respond saying,</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Yang ada pung hak maso sambayang, andia:<bt>&lt;&lt;Those who have the right to enter to worship are:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">cuma dong sa yang hati barisi,<bt>only those who have clean/holy/pure livers, [DISCOURSE: order rearranged for RL naturalness.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">cuma dong sa yang tangan sonde kotor,<bt>only those who hands are not dirty, [EXEG: TH, NET (plus note) ‘clean hands’ = ‘deeds are blameless’.] [CHECK further MTT/UNS. near syn: kotor ~ kamomos ~ dadolek]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Collocation: In terms of deeds it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">Collocation: In terms of deeds it is politik kotor, maen kotor, doi kotor</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">cuma dong sa yang sonde maen songgo,<bt>only those who do not dabble in traditional worship, [EXEG: NIV, NLT, NCV, CEV, TH (says ‘probably’)]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">cuma dong sa yang sonde angka sumpa putar-balek.<bt>only those who do not make deceitful oaths, [EXEG: NRSV, CEV, NET note; TWOT description of BART Heb gives sense of deliberate deception, not simply empty or unintentionally misleading, so KM not /omong kosong/, but more volitional /putar-balek/.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nqi (nqh): clean, innocent"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">nqi (nqh): clean, innocent</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bar: pure (commandment, heart, beloved); empty"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">bar: pure (commandment, heart, beloved); empty</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lo'-nasa': has not lifted up his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">lo'-nasa': has not lifted up his soul = long for. Could also be "no use my name wen dey make promise but dey bulai," where nefesh (especially if read "my nefesh") is synonymous with "my name"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shaw': vanity, worthlessness; generally thought to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shaw': vanity, worthlessness; generally thought to refer to idols</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mirmah: fraud, deceit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mirmah: fraud, deceit</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:8</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Orang macam bagitu dong,<bt>People of those sorts, [EXEG: ellipsed proposition to bridge from vs.4]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nanti tarima ame berkat dari TUHAN Allah.<bt>will receive *blessing from the LORD God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng orang yang babae deng Dia,<bt>And people who are in a good/right relationship with Him, [EXEG: NLT, NCV, TH, TWOT from BART Heb, (CEV undertranslated here); This parallels the phrasing we use in Romans for a similar Gk concept.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nanti rasa Dia pung hati bae,<bt>will feel/experience His *good liver (goodness/kindness/gentleness/generosity/grace). [DISCOURSE: required by RL patterns of parallelism to set up a way to get “their salvation” in. This is built on a parallel explication of 1st clause.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te Dia yang kasi salamat sang dong.<bt>cuz (elaboration) He is the one who *saves/rescue3s them, [EXEG: active proposition, rather than abstract noun.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yisa' (ns'): he will experience [blessing]"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yisa' (ns'): he will experience [blessing]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsdaqah: justice"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsdaqah: justice</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yish`o: his salvation"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yish`o: his salvation</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Batúl! Te orang macam bagitu dong,<bt>It's true! Cuz (elaboration) people of those sorts.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang ada pung hak bakumpul sama-sama<bt>are the ones who have the right to gather/assemble together</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko sambayang sang Dia.<bt>to *worship Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Orang macam bagitu dong,<bt>People of those sorts,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang suka cari Dia pung muka.<bt>are the ones who like to seek His face.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Andia, dong puji ba'i Yakob pung Allah.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is, they praise grandfather/forefather Yakob's God.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: on ‘selah’ see specific discussion in Wendland, plus NLT rendering as ‘interlude’ (also LXX); most common guess is something like ‘pause’, but Wendland's suggestion as ‘musical interlude, instruments only’ seems more likely than ‘silence’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(qs) |iSelah|r --cuma alat musik sa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">(qs) <span class="Italic">Selah</span> --cuma alat musik sa yang maen deng palán di sini</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dor: generation, but here people who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">dor: generation, but here people who share certain moral qualities</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="drshw: seeking him (qri)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">drshw: seeking him (qri)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mvaqoshe panekha ya`qov: follow LXX &quot;seek"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mvaqoshe panekha ya`qov: follow LXX "seek the face of the God of Jacob" TEV et al.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />
      <span class="Italic">[Jama'at dong minta bilang,]</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">The people/congregation request saying,</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Dengar, é!<bt>&lt;&lt;Listen, é!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Buka lebar itu pintu pagar yang ada dari dolu-dolu dong!<bt>Open wide those fence gates which have existed from long ago! [EXEG: Problem: here /tua/ ‘old, ancient’ evokes run-down, falling apart, rather than ‘eternal, enduring, always there’ evoked by the Heb, (BDB, TWOT, TH). So used “existed from long ago”.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng buka ame pintu di Ruma Sambayang,<bt>And open up the doors at the *House of Worship, [EXEG: ancient doors = temple gates, TH]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ko biar Raja yang paling hebat bisa maso di situ.&gt;&gt;<bt>so that the King who is most amazing can enter in there.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: ‘glory’ here]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="s`u ... ro'shekhem: lift your heads"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">s`u ... ro'shekhem: lift your heads (addressed to the Levites more than to the gates)? Rejoice?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sh`arim: gates"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">sh`arim: gates</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hinnas'u (ns' nif imperv): be lifted"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">hinnas'u (ns' nif imperv): be lifted up (what does that mean? Open up?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pitHey 'olam: ancient/eternal openings (doorways)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">pitHey 'olam: ancient/eternal openings (doorways)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yabo': come inside; could be that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yabo': come inside; could be that they are carrying the Box into the temple</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />
      <span class="Italic">[Kapala agama dong tanya bilang,]</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">The *priests ask saying,</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Itu Raja yang paling hebat tu, sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;That King who is most amazing, is who?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <span class="Italic">[Jama'at dong manyao bilang,]</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">The people/congregation responds saying,</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Dia tu, TUHAN,<bt>&lt;&lt;He is the LORD,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang paling kuat deng paling kuasa.<bt>who is most strong and most power/authority.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dia tu, TUHAN,<bt>He is the LORD,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang sonde parná kala dalam paráng.<bt>who has never lost in battle/war. [EXEG: Heb. strong/mighty in war/battle]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`izzuz: strong, powerful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`izzuz: strong, powerful</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gibbor: strong, mighty, hero"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">gibbor: strong, mighty, hero</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="milHamah: war"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">milHamah: war</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />Buka lebar-lebar itu pintu pagar yang ada dari dolu-dolu dong!<bt>Open wide those fence gates which have existed from long ago! [EXEG: Problem: here /tua/ ‘old, ancient’ evokes run-down, falling apart, rather than ‘eternal, enduring, always there’ evoked by the Heb, (BDB, TWOT, TH). So went with “existed from long ago”]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng buka ame pintu di Ruma Sambayang,<bt>And open up the doors at the *House of Worship, [EXEG: ancient doors = temple gates, TH]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ko biar Raja yang paling hebat bisa maso di situ!&gt;&gt;<bt>so that the King who is most amazing can enter in there.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: ‘glory’ here]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="almost the same as v. 7,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">almost the same as v. 7, except for nif`al for "open" in 7</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />
      <span class="Italic">[Kapala agama dong tanya bilang,]</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">The *priests ask saying,</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Itu Raja yang paling hebat tu, sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;That King who is most amazing is who?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <span class="Italic">[Jama'at dong manyao bilang,]</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">The people/congregation respond saying,</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Dia tu, TUHAN,<bt>&lt;&lt;He is the LORD,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang parenta samua tantara di sorga.<bt>who commands all the soldiers/armies in heaven. [EXEG: ‘Lord of hosts’ = heaven's armies, NLT, BDB, TWOT; also ‘all-powerful’ (below) from TH, BDB, TWOT, NCV, CEV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dia tu, Raja yang paling hebat!<bt>He is the one who is the most amazing King!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng Dia yang Paling Kuasa ju!&gt;&gt;<bt>And He is also the one who is Almighty/Most Powerful!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(qs) |iSelah|r -cuma alat musik sa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">(qs) <span class="Italic">Selah</span> -cuma alat musik sa yang maen deng palán di sini</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lagu puji yang angka sukur<bt>Song of praise which lifts up thanksgiving/gratitude</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="100" />
      <span class="Italic">Lagu puji yang minta tarima kasi.</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">Song of praise which gives thanks2.</span> [EXEG: Heb. towdah: praise, sacrifice of thanksgiving]</bt>
      <Annotation class="General" selectedText="towdah: praise, sacrifice of thanksgiving">
        <Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">towdah: praise, sacrifice of thanksgiving</Message>
      </Annotation>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="1" />Samua orang di anteru dunya!<bt>Everyone throughout the entire world!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Batarea rame-rame,<bt>Shout festively,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ko angka puji sang TUHAN.<bt>to lift up praise to the LORD.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hariy`uw (rw` hif imperv):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">hariy`uw (rw` hif imperv):</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Sambayang sang TUHAN,<bt>Pray/worship the LORD,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng hati sanáng.<bt>with a glad/happy liver.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Mari ko datang mangada sang Dia,<bt>Let's come (front up) before Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng manyanyi angka lagu.<bt>with singing lifting up songs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rənanah: cry of joy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rənanah: cry of joy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Mari ko mangaku bilang,<bt>Let's acknowledge/confess saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">TUHAN tu, Allah.<bt>the LORD is God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te Dia yang bekin ame sang kotong,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who has made us (accomplishment).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ais kotong jadi Dia pung milik.<bt>so (result) we-inc are/have become His possession.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Kotong yang jadi Dia pung orang.<bt>We are the ones who are His people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deng kotong sama ke domba<bt>And we are like sheep</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">yang makan rumput di Dia pung ladang dong.<bt>who eat in/at His grass. [EXEG: Heb. “sheep of his pasturage” is ambiguous. 1) sheep that eat in pastures belonging to him, 2) sheep that eat grass in pastures that he leads them to. While ‘pasture’ here is grammatically singular, in the context it can be read as generic. Context favours #1. Q: Are you sure “sheep of His pasture” is not just a way of emphasizing the care that goes with His ownership. Consider “we are his sheep He faithfully cares and provides for” or some such expression.  You may be a very idiomatic expression and you may be using it already. For "his flock" (literally the sheep of his pasture) see 74.1; 95.7. In some languages it may be necessary to recast and the sheep of his pasture to say, for example, "and the people whom he cares for." TH. UNS explanation “He is the one who guards/cares for us like we are His children.” So it is built in to the lexical choices.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mar`iytow: his pasturage"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">mar`iytow: his pasturage</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Mari ko maso lewat Dia pung pintu dong,<bt>Let's enter via His doors/gates, [EXEG: sources vague on “gates” and “courts”. Gates of city? temple? Courts = courtyard? temple? See TH and NCV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng hati yang ponu deng rasa sukur.<bt>with livers that are full of feelings of gratitude.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Mari ko maso dalam Dia pung Ruma,<bt>Let's enter into His House</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng angka puji sang Dia.<bt>lifting up praises to Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Minta tarima kasi sang Dia!<bt>Giving thanks to Him!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Puji Dia pung nama!<bt>Praising His name/reputation! [EXEG: while Heb. barəkhuw is usually glossed as ‘bless’ (cf. NRSV), many use ‘praise’ here (NLT, CEV, TB). In Timor worldview, “blessing” evokes someone calling on God to do something good to someone, so we (lower in status and power) cannot ‘bless’ God (who is higher in status and power). Clash of worldviews.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="chətserotayw: his yard"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">chətserotayw: his yard</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təhillah: glory, praise"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">təhillah: glory, praise</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="howduw (ydh hif): praise, confess"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">howduw (ydh hif): praise, confess</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="barəkhuw (imperv): bless"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">barəkhuw (imperv): bless</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Te TUHAN tu, bae.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the LORD is good.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dia pung sayang sonde tau barenti.<bt>His love/pity never ceases. (lit: does not know how to stop = unable (in character/essence) to stop)</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Apa yang Dia omong, pasti Dia bekin iko,<bt>What He says, surely/certainly He will do accordingly,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dari turunan satu pi turunan laen dong.<bt>from one (descending) generation to other generations. [EXEG: faithful in what? doing what He says? His covenent with His chosen people? Both are possible/probable. We go with our normal expression for unpacking ‘faithful’ here, since the covenenant with Israel is not in overt focus, although the ‘generations’ metaphor could certainly evoke that.]</bt><note reference="100:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Sajara Isra'el deng Yahuda 16:34, 2 Sajara Isra'el deng Yahuda 5:13, 7:3, Esra 3:11, Lagu Puji dong 106:1, 107:1, 118:1, 136:1, Yeremia 33:11</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan tu, yang jaga sang kotong<bt>God2 is the one who guards/watches over us-inc</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="121" />
      <span class="Italic">Lagu puji waktu kotong mau maso pi sambayang.</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">Song of praise when we-inc are going to/about to enter to pray/worship.</span>
      </bt>
      <note reference="121" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Cuma ada satu Ruma Sambayang Pusat sa, andia di kota Yerusalem. Jadi orang Yahudi dari mana-mana musti pi dari jao ko sambayang deng bekin korban macam-macam di situ. Te korban binatang dong, cuma bole kasi di Ruma Sambayang Pusat sa. Andia ko banya orang datang dari jao-jao ko sambayang di situ. Dong tu, <span class="Italic">ziarah</span>, te dong maksud pi dari agama pung mau-mau. Ini lagu puji ni, yang dong angka waktu mau maso pi dalam Ruma Sambayang Pusat.<bt>There is just one *Temple (Main Worship House), that is, in Yerusalem. So (consequently) Yahudi people from many places must go from afar to pray/worship and make various sacrifices there. Cuz (elaboration) the animal sacrifices could only be given at the *Temple. That is why many people came from far away places to pray/worship there. They were <span class="Italic">ziarah</span> (pilgrims: unassimilated Arabic loan), cuz (elaboration) their purpose for going was from religious requirements. This song of praise here is what they lifted up/spoke out when they were going to enter into the *Temple.</bt></note>
    </p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="1" />Beta ni, susa!<bt>I here am in difficulty! [EXEG: Implicit background for this “psalm of protection”. See NET notes “The psalmist assumes the dramatic role of one needing help.”, IVP background comm. and TH. Note also that TH and NET notes observe that this whole psalm is set up as an “obvious dialogue” which is how we've structured it.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Andia ko beta lia-lia pi gunung ko cari-cari,<bt>That is why I keep looking at the mountains/hills to keep trying to find out,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ais beta tanya bilang,<bt>so/then I ask saying, [EXEG: Heb is not marked who he is asking. 1) himself? 2) others? So we leave it open.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Yang mau tolong ame sang beta,<bt>&lt;The one who is going to help me (successfully),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nanti datang dari mana?<bt>will come from where? [EXEG: Heb. ‘where?’ is interrogative, so versions where it is treated as a statement (see TH) are weak in reflecting the style of the Heb.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Kira-kira dari sana, ko?&gt;<bt>Perhaps from there, ko? [+tag]&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`ezri (`ezer): my help, help for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`ezri (`ezer): my help, help for me</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Padahal yang mau tolong sang beta tu,<bt>Whereas in fact, the one who is going to help me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bukan datang dari gunung.<bt>doesn't come from the mountains.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te yang tolong sang beta ni,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the one who helps me here,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">andia, TUHAN Allah,<bt>is the LORD God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">yang bekin ame langit deng bumi.<bt>who made heaven and earth (accomplishment).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Dia yang jaga sang bosong.<bt>He is the one who guards you-pl.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dia yang sonde kasi biar ko bosong jato.<bt>He is the one who does not allow for you to fall (physically, morally, spiritually, socially). [EXEG: TH: ‘He will not let your foot be moved/waver/stumble’ means “He will not let you stumble (or, fall),” a figure for “falling” into misfortune or trouble.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Deng yang jaga deng piara sang bosong tu,<bt>And that one who guards and takes care of you-pl,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="remove deng?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">remove deng?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sonde jato tatidor sadiki ju.<bt>does not (accidentally) fall asleep either. [NOTE to daughter translations: you may or may not be able to preserve the play on words in the Kupang “fall” ... “fall asleep”. Don't force it.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'al-yiten lamot: he will not allow"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'al-yiten lamot: he will not allow your feet to waver, stumble</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="'al-yanum (nwm): fall asleep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">'al-yanum (nwm): fall asleep</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Te yang jaga tarús sang bangsa Isra'el tu,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) that one who continually guards the people of Isra'el,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sonde tau tatidor,<bt>never sleeps [NOTE: KM lit: doesn't know how to sleep. Grammatical construction implies it is not in his nature.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">deng sonde tau sonu.<bt>and never deep sleeps2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="One MTT wanted: sonde tau tasonu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">One MTT wanted: sonde tau tasonu to be parallel in structure, but several others said it really stuck out as awkward.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shomer: guard, security guard, military guard"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shomer: guard, security guard, military guard</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishan (yshn): go to sleep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yishan (yshn): go to sleep</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Batúl! TUHAN Allah sandiri yang jaga ame sang bosong!<bt>That's true! The LORD God himself is the one who guards you-pl (successfully)!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dia yang badiri di bosong pung sablá,<bt>He is the one who is standing at your-pl side,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko pele ame sang bosong,<bt>to block/protect you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sama ke pohon pung sombar pele ame sang kotong dari matahari pung panas.<bt>like the shade of a tree blocks/protects you from the heat of the sun. [EXEG: Heb. tsel: shade, protection.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsel: shade, protection"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsel: shade, protection</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Ais kalo siang hari,<bt>So/then when it is daytime,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">matahari sonde bekin angus sang bosong,<bt>the sun is not going to burn you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Deng kalo malam hari,<bt>And when it is night time,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bulan sonde bekin bosong jadi saki.<bt>the moon is not going to make you become sick/hurt. [EXEG: ‘moon’ here is simply a synonymous parallelism with ‘sun’. See also NET note.] [NOTE to daughter translations: what the moon does has to make some sort of sense. The Heb “strike, smite” can be in physically as in war, or socially, or through disease.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yomam: during the day"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yomam: during the day</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lo'-yakhekha (nkh hif): will not strike"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">lo'-yakhekha (nkh hif): will not strike you, bring illness on you, wound you</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yareach: moon, older word"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yareach: moon, older word</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Te TUHAN mau jaga ame bosong<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the LORD is going to guard you-pl</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dari samua yang jahat;<bt>from all that is evil;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">deng Dia yang piara ame bosong<bt>and He is the one who takes care of you</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ko biar bosong idop aman.<bt>so that you can live in safety. [EXEG: Heb. he will guard your life/soul. CEV “he will keep you safe from all dangers.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="yishmor et-nafshekha: he will guard your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">yishmor et-nafshekha: he will guard your life/soul</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />TUHAN jaga bosong pung dudu-badiri,<bt>The LORD guards your situation (lit: sitting-standing)</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">waktu bosong kaluar-maso pi mana-mana,<bt>when you are exiting-entering anywhere.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaluar-maso NOT clear to MTTs"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z">kaluar-maso NOT clear to MTTs</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dari sakarang, tarús-tarús,<bt>from now, continually,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sampe salamanya sonde pake barenti.<bt>until forever without ceasing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tse'tkha (yts'): when you leave"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tse'tkha (yts'): when you leave</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Angka puji sang Tuhan Allah!<bt>Lift up praise to the Lord God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <c n="150" />
      <v n="1" />Puji TUHAN!<bt>Praise the LORD!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Puji Tuhan Allah,<bt>Praise the Lord God,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang ada dalam Dia pung Ruma Sambayang!<bt>who is in His *House of Prayer/Worship!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang ada di langit yang paling luas!<bt>who is in the broadest sky/heaven! [EXEG: Heb. rqiya`: expanse. In RL ‘mighty’ does not collocate with sky/heavens.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`uzzo: his strength, might, power, refuge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`uzzo: his strength, might, power, refuge</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="qadsho: his holy thing, holy place,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">qadsho: his holy thing, holy place, holiness</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rqiya`: expanse. UBS &quot;For both phrases"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rqiya`: expanse. UBS "For both phrases the preposition in indicates where God is, not where those are who are urged to praise him"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal samua yang Dia bekin ame, talalu hebat!<bt>because everything that He has made/created (accomplishment svc = serial verb construction), is so very amazing/impressive!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tagal Dia pung nama lebe hebat dari samua!<bt>because His name/reputation is more amazing than than every(thing/one)! [EXEG: Heb. according to the greatness1 of his greatness2 = NRSV: according to his surpassing greatness.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gvurotayw: his strength, force, might deeds"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">gvurotayw: his strength, force, might deeds</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rov: abundance"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">rov: abundance</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gudlo: greatness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">gudlo: greatness</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng tiop tarompet ukur kuat.<bt>by blowing the trumpet (loan used 29 times in the NT) with all your might/as loud as you can. (lit: measuring strong)</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pake alat musik, ke sasando!<bt>using musical instruments, like the sasando! [NOTE: local harp-like instrument with 9-42 strings around the outside of a piece of bamboo, played with all ten fingers, using a lontar-palm (Borassus sp.) leaf as the sound board. See Wikpedia article for photos.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teqa`: blast of a horn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">teqa`: blast of a horn</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shofar: trumpet, ram's horn; played by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shofar: trumpet, ram's horn; played by priests. It sounds like a conch shell. d</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nevel: lyre; played by the Levite"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">nevel: lyre; played by the Levite assistants to the priests. Because it is usually listed together with other instruments, some think it may have been the bass</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kinnor: harp; also the Levites"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">kinnor: harp; also the Levites</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng puku tifa, deng baronggeng.<bt>by/with beating the drum, and (local) dancing.</bt></p>
    <fig path="Hk-lb\BK00174c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Alat musik<bt>Musical instruments</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pake alat musik sanár, deng tiop suling!<bt>using stringed musical instruments, and blowing (bamboo) flutes! [NOTE: the term for stringed instruments uses a common word for fishline, and refers to (local and foreign varieties of) instruments like guitars, ukuleles, and violins. either strummed or plucked or using a bow.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="`ugav: flute"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">`ugav: flute</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tof: tambourine; played by ordinary people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tof: tambourine; played by ordinary people</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maHol: round dance"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">maHol: round dance</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="minnim: string instruments"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">minnim: string instruments</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng pake gong kici!<bt>by using small gongs! [NOTE: these are usually on a pentatonic scale, and come in sets of 5-9 gongs.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Puji sang Dia,<bt>Praise Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng puku gong bésar ju!<bt>by hitting the big gong as well!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tsiltsley: cymbals"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">tsiltsley: cymbals</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="shama` (shema`): sound; small, vertically-held cymbals."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">shama` (shema`): sound; small, vertically-held cymbals. UBS "flat metal plates which were struck together"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="təru`ah: shout, alarm; large, horizontally-held cymbals."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">təru`ah: shout, alarm; large, horizontally-held cymbals. UBS "metal cones, one of which was brought down on top of the other, on the larger end. They were probably made out of bronze"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Mari ko samua yang ada pung napas,<bt>Come on [+hortative] so that everything which has [its] breath,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">manyanyi rame-rame,<bt>sings festively,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko angka puji sang TUHAN Allah!<bt>to lift up praises to the LORD God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Puji TUHAN!<bt>Praise the LORD!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nshamah: blast (of wind); breath; breath"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2015-05-15 14:05:29Z" status="Information">nshamah: blast (of wind); breath; breath of life; breathing beings; breath (of God)</Message></Annotation></p>
  </book>
</bible>